<TITLE> Bangladesh looks to $1bn trade volume with Turkey: adviser </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Aug 24 (bdnews24.com)  Commerce adviser Hossain Zillur Rahman has said Bangladesh's trade volume with Turkey, the seventh largest economy in the world, could reach $1 billion in the near future, according to a statement released Sunday. Bangladesh achieved its fiscal 2007-08 export target of $220 million to Turkey within the first five months of the year; at present Bangladesh's exports to Turkey total US$ 289 million out of a total trade volume of $352 million, the adviser was quoted as saying by the press information department. Zillur Rahmanwho met with industries and trade minister Mehmel Zafer Caglayan on Fridaysaid Turkey has shown most interest in Bangladesh's readymade garments, shipbuilding and textile sectors. The adviser added that pharmaceuticals, energy and petroleum, leather and ceramic could also be potential sectors for future trade and investment between the two countries. Hossain Zillur was leading the Bangladesh delegation to the formal inauguration of the 77th Izmir International Fair. The adviser said the Turkish minister was optimistic about Bangladesh-Turkey joint ventures could competing in the world market. Zillur Rahman requested Caglayan to ease its banking system for businesspersons to easily remit and receive currencies. Turkish investors could take advantage of the cheap labour, tax holidays and other infrastructural supports for investment in Bangladesh, the adviser said. bd
